1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:03,418
I know you're tempted to skip ahead.

2
00:00:03,368 --> 00:00:04,750
Don't.

3
00:00:04,750 --> 00:00:09,000
This is the part that gets asked in interviews.

4
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:13,671
Enabled with enable.idempotence=true.

5
00:00:13,671 --> 00:00:19,605
The broker assigns each producer instance a Producer ID (PID).

6
00:00:19,605 --> 00:00:28,078
The producer assigns a sequence number to every batch per partition, starting at 0 and incrementing.

7
00:00:28,078 --> 00:00:37,473
When a retry arrives, the broker checks: have I already written a batch with this PID + partition + sequence number?

8
00:00:37,473 --> 00:00:46,315
If yes, it silently discards the duplicate without returning an error , which is pretty wild if you think about it.

9
00:00:46,315 --> 00:00:52,894
Interviewers have a favorite trap question about Mechanism 2: Transactional Producer.

10
00:00:52,894 --> 00:00:56,605
90 percent of candidates fall for it.

11
00:00:56,605 --> 00:01:00,486
I will show you the trap and how to avoid it.

